#   POST-002: `be post '#msg'` misparses a dotted multi-line message as a path

`be post` should treat a `#`-led argument as the commit message, never a path ŌĆö but a multi-line message that also contains a dot is misrouted to path-form and refused ("path-form URI ŌĆ” not allowed"), so only the legacy `-m` flag works. The defect is in the **pre-parse argument interpretation** (`DOGNormalizeArg`, `dog/DOG.c:207`), NOT in the URI grammar: a `#`-led arg is classified `starts_uri` and fed to the RFC-strict URILexer, which cannot hold a newline in a fragment, so the message's tail spills into `u->path`. The URI grammar is already RFC 3986-compliant and MUST stay so ŌĆö widening `URIFragment` to `( any* )` is the WRONG fix (rejected: it discards the RFC character-class structure, admitting NUL/control bytes). The goal: any `#`-led message commits verbatim, regardless of dots or newlines, with the grammar untouched. See [POST], [URI].

##  Issues
The `#`-led message is funnelled into the URILexer-as-path instead of into the fragment slot verbatim.

 -  `DOGNormalizeArg` (`dog/DOG.c:207`) sets `starts_uri = YES` for any arg whose first byte is `#` (`:238`) and immediately `return DOGParseURI(u, arg)` (`:264-267`) ŌĆö sending the whole message through the URILexer.
 -  The lexer's fragment is RFC 3986 `fragment = *( pchar / "/" / "?" )` (`abc/URI.c.rl:251`) and correctly STOPS at the first `\n` (a newline is not a `pchar`). The un-`#`'d tail (which contains a `.`) then ends up in `u->path` ŌĆö i.e. "the message was seen as a path because the part after the newline had no `#` in front of it."
 -  `be_post_is_path_form` (`beagle/BE.cli.c:1855`) returns YES on a non-empty `u->path` (`:1857`) BEFORE its raw-byte `.`/`/` scan (`:1864`, which skips a leading `?` but not `#`); so `BEActPathFormCheck`'s pure-fragment skip (`:1878`, needs `path` empty) never fires and POST refuses (`:1880-1886`).
 -  The correct free-text handling already exists one branch lower (`dog/DOG.c:270-277`): a whitespace token that does NOT start with a sigil is dropped straight into the fragment slot verbatim (no URILexer). A `#`-led message never reaches it because `starts_uri` is tested first ŌĆö the bug is this routing order/logic, not the grammar.
 -  Single-line dotted messages and dot-free multi-line messages parse fine; the bug needs BOTH a newline and a `.`. The standard `Co-Authored-By: <name> <a@b.c>` trailer triggers it on essentially every real commit, forcing the legacy `-m` flag.

##  Blockers
None. The URI grammar must remain RFC 3986-compliant (do NOT widen `URIFragment`); the fix is confined to the pre-parse classifier.

##  Planned
Route a `#`-led arg's message into the fragment verbatim in the pre-parse classifier; leave the grammar and the lexer untouched.

 -  In `DOGNormalizeArg` (`dog/DOG.c`), special-case an arg whose first byte is `#`: assign the bytes AFTER the `#` to `u->fragment` verbatim (advance past the `#` with a typed slice op ŌĆö NO pointer arithmetic, per [CLAUDE] ┬¦10), leave `path`/`query`/`authority`/`scheme` empty, and do NOT call the URILexer. This mirrors the existing `has_ws ŌåÆ fragment` bypass and uniformly handles `#fix`, `#a\n\nCo-Authored-By: ŌĆ”`, and a message containing `be://` (no `//`-collapse ŌĆö overlaps [POST-007]). Once `path` is empty, `BEActPathFormCheck`'s pure-fragment skip handles the rest (keep it as belt-and-suspenders).
 -  Keep the URILexer fragment rule (`abc/URI.c.rl:251`) exactly as-is ŌĆö RFC 3986 compliant. A raw newline in a URI fragment is NOT valid RFC; the message is opaque payload handled OUTSIDE the grammar, the same way Beagle handles free-text search.
 -  Repro-first ([CLAUDE] ┬¦17): a `DOGNormalizeArg`-level unit case asserting `#a\n\nCo-Authored-By: X <a@b.c>` yields `fragment` = the whole post-`#` body and EMPTY `path`; plus the end-to-end `test/post/34-msg-multiline-dot` asserting `be post '#<multiline dotted>'` commits the body verbatim and is NOT refused, with `-m` still working. Both fail before the fix.
 -  NOTE: the first attempt widened `URIFragment` to `( any* )` and regenerated the ragel ŌĆö REJECTED for breaking RFC compliance. A new worker must revert any grammar/`URI.rl.c` change and implement the classifier fix above.

